poem:
The Sciencefairgaw

Twas glowling in the labbrume, and the sprocket-gleams did wink;
The posterbeaks were stapled tight, the fizzles bubbled pink;
The fluxlings drank the copper-smoke, the placard-gnomes did stare
At whirry bits and glassy jars and circuits everywhere.

"Beware the Sputtergaw, my child! the Sputtergaw, beware!
Its fizzing jaws and sparking paws, its breath of ozone air!
The Flubbulon with bubbleplume will bluster, boom, and fail;
The Glitchling creeps in code at night and tangles every rail."

He soldered slyly, clip-clap-clung, he tighten-tosed each screw;
He fed the robot kernel-crumbs, and coaxed the LEDs anew;
He tweaked the gearwhorl, cranked the pump, and hummed a jitter-song —
Then marched his model, steady-smown, to face the swap and wrong.

The Sputtergaw did sputter-snap, it fizzed and flared a curl;
Its dousing huffs made posters droop and made the voltmeters whirl;
But spangle-wits and steady-hand, with clamp and cord and grin,
They braided wires, reversed the short, and calmed the circuit's din.

They pressed the switch — a bright whuzzboom! — the Sputtergaw went still;
The LEDs like clustered stars blinked proud atop the sill;
The judges clapped their clipper-hands, the prizes chimed like rain,
And every tinker's scrappy heart felt curious and plain.

Twas glowling in the labbrume, and sprocket-gleams did wink;
The posterbeaks were stapled tight, the fizzles bubbled pink;
So keep your clamp and copper-thought and code that sings, not snarls,
And fear no sputter-gaws where dreams and Maker-magic swirls.

The Monte-Carloquy

'Twas glint-time, and the marbled docks did shimmer, sway and sing;
The yachts all yawed like sleepy whales, the café-lamps burned low;
Croupiers hummed their velvet rhymes and gowns like seabirds took wing,
While lemon-lights in laneways threw a honeyed, glancing glow.

Beware the Roulettiff, my son! the wheel that whispers "spin!";
Beware the Baccarat-bob, the slot-sneer and the rack;
Beware the croupier's sly-silver grin that threads the gamester's skin;
Shun glitterfang and velvet-glow that nuzzle at your back.

He took his doré chip in hand; long time the glitter-thing he sought;
So rested he beside the quay where night-sea murmurs spoke;
And, as the moon sipped foam and sky, the Roulettiff with clack and knot
Came whiffling down the esplanade and left a trail of smoke.

One, two! One, two! And through and through the doré token flew;
He struck the spinning argent wheel—its clatter snapped and sighed;
The ball went glim, the pockets chimed, the croupiers blinked askew,
And out there leapt the jackpot-gleam that rolled along the tide.

"O frabjous-night! Callooh! Monte!" cried the players, cap in hand;
He bore the glitter-prize aloft; the promenades all cheered;
The bandiff brayed, the yachts chimed bells, and lamps like brass and sand
Cast ripples on the silver slate where sudden fortunes reared.

And when the dawn uncurtained cliffs and tawny seagulls cried,
The Monte-mouth slowed its murmur, gamblers' footfalls thinned;
Yet strangers come with pocket-chips and wide-eyed, hopeful pride,
To meet the Roulettiff's winking grin and try their luck within.

Layover Bay

’Twas gloamig at Layover Bay, and the quiv’ring ferries swam;
The baggage-beetles burbled low, the cronny gulls went blam;
All bumbly carts were stowed and tied, and clockwings ticked their tune,
While passengers in pocketed coats did snooze beneath the noon.

“Hark!” called the portly slip-shank guard, “mind the loiter-loam and tide,
Mind the rumble-rip of the drift, and the sloop-sighs that hide;
Lest the layover-thing, with blinkered eyes and trunks of tumbling maw,
Slip from the fog with a clattering cain, and gawp at what he saw.”

From brackle-brine and ropy reeds the Layover-creep did creep,
With luggageed legs and tumbled tag, it shuffled slow and deep;
Its handle-hands held sundry things — a toothbrush, comb, and hat —
And every strap and sticker sang a scrap of someone’s chat.

“Bewear the drabble-moor!” cried one who’d lost a sock to fate,
“For it snatches spare itineries and stamps them ere too late.”
The layover-thing it sniffed the pier, it snuffled near the quay,
And lantern-light in its beard went flicker-fleck and free.

Then forth there strode a twig of youth with ticket clenched and brave,
He twirled a soggy boarding pass and hummed a hummocky stave;
He drew his spare-time scarf of blue, his satchel-sabre bright,
And faced the beast on creaking planks beneath the waiting light.

They tussled through the tunnel-mist where shuttle-sparrows stare,
He dodged a flung-out backpack-gnash, he spun with porchlight flare;
With one clean snip — a ribbon-snap — the creature coughed and sighed,
Its trolley-tendons loosened up and all its stickers flied.

The layover-thing lay Lull’d and low; the bay gave up a cheer;
The portly guard unlatched his hat and polished up his leer;
“Three cheers for those who brave the wait, who brave the layover’s game!”
And travelers reclaimed their lost mitts and stamps of faded name.

’Twas gloamig no more at Layover Bay; the moon made ripples bright;
The baggage-beetles hummed anew, the ferries hummed good-night;
And every tag and timorous heart found onward paths to sway —
So mind your straps at Layover Bay when twilight meets the quay.

The Third‑Rail Thrum

Twas brummig, and the flicker-baffles
Did whump upon the midnight quay;
The humble-rails in silver gaffles
Did buzzle with an urchin’s glee;
And out there slung the sparklèd seam,
A shivery, shuddery, humming-gleam.

"Beware the Third‑Rail Thrum, my son!
The zizzle-rail that crooneth low;
Beware its snap, its fizzle-run,
The toe-tugged zap that lays men low;
Grip not its lip, nor finger-glide,
For flash and fizz will sweep aside."

He took his boot of rubbersfine,
His glovedle hand, his steady stick;
He tippled-tip on creeper-line,
And hummed his hum-hush humming trick;
With clamp and click and snicker-spark,
He muffled down the hungry dark.

And home they went with caution-brim:
"We'll mind the rail, keep distance true;
Its hum is old, its whisper grim,
But not for meddle-madmen's due;
So mark this tale, ye platform-folk,
And heed the Third‑Rail's quiet spoke."
